true_message:
Remove connection string from log message

A connection string containing an unsupported option generates a log
message at warning level to the "org.mongodb.driver.uri" component. The
log message contains the full connection string.  As the connection
string may contain the credentials used to authenticate, it should not
be logged.  This commit removes the full connection string from the log
message, and instead just logs the name of the unsupported option.

JAVA-<I>

Steam Store URL path update

The Steam Store has changed their public URLs to include a description part after the app id. Unfortunately, anything included after the /widget iframe path now fails to resolve. This change takes the app id from the URL only and puts the widget/{app_id} part on.



Examples:



Old URL from Steam store page: <URL>: <URL>

Updated Steam Store Onebox URL extraction to correctly handle app IDs in the Steam store URL

Explanation:
The change involves modifying the way the application extracts the URL for a Steam Store Onebox. Previously, it was simply removing "/app/" from the URL. Now, it uses a regular expression to find and remove the "/app/" substring only when it is part of a valid Steam store app ID link. This ensures that the correct URL structure is used when generating the HTML code for the Onebox.

true_message:
Allow weak tags to be processed by sprockets.

Since nginx <I>, strong ETags are transformed into weak ETags "starting with W/" if the request is compressed. That means that when the browser re-requests the assets in development mode, sprockets will see an ETag starting with "W/..." which will never match, and as such, cache will never work. So I'm relaxing the regex here a little to handle that.
generated_message: Updated Sprockets server to match and ignore assets based on case-sensitive ETag in HTTP headers.

goquery.NewDocumentFromResponse is deprecated
generated_message:
Closed connection to HTTP response body after parsing with goquery

Explanation: This commit changes the method used to create a goquery.Document object from an http.Response struct. Instead of using goquery.NewDocumentFromResponse directly, it now creates a defer statement to close the response body before creating the document using goquery.NewDocumentFromReader on the response's Body reader. This ensures that the HTTP connection is properly closed after the response has been parsed by goquery.
